{"cells": [{"cell_type": "markdown", "metadata": {}, "source": ["# Descriptive Statistics, Probability Distributions, and Visualization Techniques\n\nThis Jupyter notebook encompasses various foundational concepts in statistics, probability, and visualization techniques, focusing on their applications in analyzing Epson production trends and machine quality.\n\n## 1. Descriptive Statistics\n\nDescriptive statistics provide a summary of the data and its features. Here are the main metrics we will cover:\n\n- **Mean**: The average of the data set.\n- **Median**: The middle value separating the higher half from the lower half of the data set.\n- **Mode**: The value that appears most frequently in a data set.\n- **Standard Deviation**: A measure of the amount of variation or dispersion of a set of values.\n- **Variance**: The expectation of the squared deviation of a random variable from its mean.\n    \n```python\nimport numpy as np\n\ndata = np.random.randn(100)  # Generating random data\nmean = np.mean(data)\nmedian = np.median(data)\nmode = stats.mode(data)\nstd_dev = np.std(data)\nvariance = np.var(data)\n\nprint(f'Mean: {mean}, Median: {median}, Mode: {mode.mode[0]}, Std Dev: {std_dev}, Variance: {variance}')\n```\n\n## 2. Probability Distributions\n\nProbability distributions describe how the values of a variable are distributed. We will cover two common distributions:\n\n- **Normal Distribution**: This is symmetric around the mean, showing that data near the mean are more frequent in occurrence than data far from the mean.\n- **Binomial Distribution**: This represents the number of successes in a fixed number of trials.\n    \n```python\nimport matplotlib.pyplot as plt\nimport seaborn as sns\n\n# Normal Distribution\nn = 1000\nmean = 0\nstd_dev = 1\nx = np.random.normal(mean, std_dev, n)\nsns.histplot(x, bins=30, kde=True)\nplt.title('Normal Distribution')\nplt.xlabel('Value')\nplt.ylabel('Frequency')\nplt.show()\n\n# Binomial Distribution\nn_trials = 10\np_success = 0.5\nbinomial_data = np.random.binomial(n_trials, p_success, n)\nsns.histplot(binom_data, bins=30, kde=True)\nplt.title('Binomial Distribution')\nplt.xlabel('Number of Successes')\nplt.ylabel('Frequency')\nplt.show()\n```\n\n## 3. Visualization Techniques\n\nVisualizing data is crucial for understanding trends and underlying patterns. We will use **Matplotlib** and **Seaborn** for visualization.\n\n### 3.1 Matplotlib Example\n```python\nimport matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n\ncategories = ['A', 'B', 'C', 'D']\nvalues = [10, 15, 7, 12]\nplt.bar(categories, values)\nplt.ylabel('Values')\nplt.title('Bar Chart Example')\nplt.show()\n```\n\n### 3.2 Seaborn Example\n```python\nsns.boxplot(x='categories', y='values', data=df)\nplt.title('Boxplot Example')\nplt.show()\n```\n\n## 4. Epson Production Trends\n\nIn this section, we will analyze trends in Epson's production data. We will use historical data to visualize production levels over time.\n\n```python\n# Suppose df is a DataFrame with production data\ndf['date'] = pd.to_datetime(df['date'])\ndf.set_index('date').resample('M').sum()['production'].plot()\nplt.title('Epson Production Trends Over Time')\nplt.xlabel('Date')\nplt.ylabel('Production Volume')\nplt.show()\n```\n\n## 5. Machine Quality Analysis\n\nFinally, we will analyze machine quality data to identify problems and trends over time.\n```python\ndf['quality'].value_counts().plot(kind='bar')\nplt.title('Machine Quality Analysis')\nplt.xlabel('Quality Category')\nplt.ylabel('Frequency')\nplt.show()\n```\n\n---\nThis concludes our notebook on Descriptive Statistics, Probability Distributions, and Visualization Techniques. \n"]}